The mound is circular, measuring 95 meters in diameter and 12.7 meters in height (prior to excavations, it was thought to be 55 meters in diameter).{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} It is the second-largest circular kofun in Nara Prefecture, following the {{ill|Tomio Maruyama Kofun|ja|富雄丸山古墳}} in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市}} (109 meters in diameter). The mound consists of two tiers.<ref name="Yamatotakada City">[http://www.city.yamatotakada.nara.jp/city/rekishi/iseki/kofun/konpira.html Konpirayama Kofun] - Yamatotakada City Official Website.</ref> Artifacts such as cylindrical haniwa were found on the terraces and mound summit, including shield-shaped and house-shaped haniwa from the summit and lid-shaped haniwa from the slopes.{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} Miniature pottery was discovered inside two cylindrical haniwa, similar to finds at other notable kofun such as {{ill|Otomeyama Kofun|ja|乙女山古墳}} and {{ill|Shibuya Mukaiyama Kofun|ja|渋谷向山古墳}}.<ref name="Yamatotakada City"/> The mound is surrounded by a moat. However, its burial facilities and grave goods remain unknown.
This kofun is estimated to have been built in the early 5th century (mid-Kofun period).{{Sfn|Konpira Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} The Makimuku Kofun Cluster features a notable pattern where large keyhole-shaped mounds and circular mounds (or scallop-shell mounds) are constructed in close proximity. This arrangement has been linked to the {{ill|Hime-Hiko System|ja|ヒメヒコ制}}, a governance structure based on dual leadership.{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}}
