'''Konpirayama Kofun''' (コンピラ山古墳) is a [[kofun]] (ancient Kofun) located in {{ill|Yamatotakada City|ja|大和高田市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatotakada City|qq=}}, Nara Prefecture. It is a circular Kofun (円墳) and part of the {{ill|Makimuku Kofun Cluster|ja|馬見古墳群|1=Umami Kofun Cluster|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Makimuku Kofun Cluster|13=User:Immanuelle/Umami Kofun Cluster|qq=}} (Southern Group within the Tsukiyama Kofun Cluster). This kofun is not Historic Site1 as a historic site.

== Overview ==
[[File:Tukiyama kofun 01.jpg|250px|thumb|right|{{center|Tsukiyama Kofun Cluster}}{{small|{{National Aerial Photograph}}}}]]
The Konpirayama Kofun is a large circular Kofun built to the east of {{ill|Tsukiyama Kofun (Yamatotakada)|ja|築山古墳 (大和高田市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukiyama Kofun (Yamatotakada)|qq=}} (Historic Site1 as the Iwazono {{ill|Mausoleum Reference Site|ja|陵墓参考地|1=Mausoleum Reference Site|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mausoleum Reference Site|13=User:Immanuelle/Mausoleum Reference Site|qq=}}) at the southern end of the Makimuku Hills in the western Nara Basin. Previously considered an {{ill|Baizuka|ja|陪塚|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baizuka|qq=}} (associated mound) of the Tsukiyama Kofun, recent boundary-confirmation excavations have been conducted, revealing its true significance.{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}}

The mound is circular, measuring 95 meters in diameter and 12.7 meters in height (prior to excavations, it was thought to be 55 meters in diameter).{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} It is the second-largest circular kofun in Nara Prefecture, following the {{ill|Tomio Maruyama Kofun|ja|富雄丸山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomio Maruyama Kofun|qq=}} in {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara City|qq=}} (109 meters in diameter). The mound consists of two tiers.<ref name="Yamatotakada City">[http://www.city.yamatotakada.nara.jp/city/rekishi/iseki/kofun/konpira.html Konpirayama Kofun] - Yamatotakada City Official Website.</ref> burial goods such as cylindrical haniwa were found on the terraces and mound summit, including shield-shaped and house-shaped haniwa from the summit and lid-shaped haniwa from the slopes.{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} Miniature pottery was discovered inside two cylindrical haniwa, similar to finds at other notable kofun such as {{ill|Otomeyama Kofun|ja|乙女山古墳|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otomeyama Kofun|qq=}} and {{ill|Shibuya Mukaiyama Kofun|ja|渋谷向山古墳|1=Shibutani Mukoyama Kofun|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibuya Mukaiyama Kofun|13=User:Immanuelle/Shibutani Mukoyama Kofun|qq=}}.<ref name="Yamatotakada City"/> The mound is surrounded by a moat. However, its burial facilities and grave goods remain unknown.

This kofun is estimated to have been built in the early 5th century (mid-Kofun period).{{Sfn|Konpira Kofun (Zoku Kofun)|2002}}{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}} The Makimuku Kofun Cluster features a notable pattern where large keyhole-shaped mounds and circular mounds (or scallop-shell mounds) are constructed in close proximity. This arrangement has been linked to the {{ill|Hime-Hiko System|ja|ヒメヒコ制|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hime-Hiko System|qq=}}, a governance structure based on dual leadership.{{Sfn|Kawakami Kunihiko|2006}}

